Dear NC Leaders:

I will be brief, but I want to point out some of the many flaws in the proposed Racial Justice Act.

My husband was murdered in Forsyth County almost 16 years ago.  My family has been from trial through 9 years of appeals to clemency hearing to witnessing the execution of Robbie Lyons.  Lyons shot my husband multiple times in our business in an attempted armed robbery.  Before his execution, he had 40 some infractions and punched a guard in the eye.

  I have been a very active advocate for crime victims since that time.  Yes, I could spend my time doing many things that I would enjoy better, but most people will never understand the passion of victims who seek to be heard, rights for victims with our laws, and most of all justice for a heinous murder and for the punishment to be carried out.

*There are 163 death row murderers with 270 victims, and victim's families will have to wait more years to have justice.  With the execution of the murderer comes some peace and relief of the fear that this murderer will not hurt anyone again.  With life sentences there is always the possibly of release by sentence being overturned, clerical error, pardoned, change in law such as with this Racial Act.

*Consider the safety of the state's citizens when death sentences are changed to life and those murderers sentenced before Oct. 1994 will be released after 20 years in prison.

*Justice and punishment should be based on guilt.  Juries must weigh the aggravated and mitigating factors.  Race should not be one of the factors.

*I see this bill as a means to end capital punishment; however, there remains a large majority of public support for the death penalty for the taking of a person's life.

*In the appeals process of 10+ years the proceedings are reviewed by some 30 judges and reviewed for proportionality to other cases.

*I must point out that Rep. Womble's statement that Darryl Hunt was almost executed
is not true.  Hunt was NEVER on death row.

*There have been more whites executed in the US and in NC than blacks.  There is no proof of an innocent person being executed since 1900.

*Studies from various universities have indicated that murders do increase significantly when there is no capital punishment.

*NC should not spare murderers at the cost of sacrificing more innocent lives.

If this bill is passed, families will have more years added to the appeals process before they will see justice carried out.  In the courtroom, families should not have to hear that the murderer of their loved one cannot be tried for his life because of racial quotas.  Taxpayers should not have to pay for duplication of the safeguards that are already in place.

Comments I have heard from family, friends, church members, crime victims, letters to editors of newspapers are what a stupid bill.  People can easily see what the motivation is behind this bill.

I urge you to take a stand for the citizens of this state and VOTE NO.

Ramona Stafford
Forsyth County



