Dear Senator:

The NC Racial Justice Act (SB461) has been recalendared for today.  This is still bad legislation as I have sited to you by email and phone calls to you this week.

My husband was murdered in 1993 for an attempted armed robbery of our business.  My family has been from trial through 9 years of appeals, clemency hearing and execution in 2003.  I can so understand the angrier and frustration by families who have the murderer on death row and will be faced with more years of delay if this bill is passed.

I have such sadness for those families who will be sitting in courtrooms across our state
trusting in our system of juries to find the guilty person and the punishment they deserve for taking the life of their loved one.  If this bill is passed, only to find that punishment is measured by quotas/statistics/percentages based on race rather than by the weight of the evidence, aggravating and mitigating factors.  It is up to twelve people to weigh that evidence and determine the punishment.  Legislators you must hold murderers accountable not by allowing them to have a lesser sentence because of race, nationality etc.

When Rep. Womble stood and spoke on the floor of the House recently, he failed to tell and describe the brutal murders the death row defendants committed.  Prosecutors really do not know how many shots were aimed at my husband, but they do know that he was hit three times with one of those the gun put to his back and the murderer kept shooting until he emptied the gun.  I have listened to other trials where the defendant repeatedly used a tire iron until their victim was dead.  You do not hear about the victim only that the murderer is getting punishment that he does not deserve.  You will not hear about the victim today either.

I know you are busy legislators and will not continue to tell you how bad this bill is for the safety of the public as university studies have shown that murders do increase when there is no capital punishment.  Crime victims will be hugely impacted, and it cannot be known if next year there will be a proposed bill to change the sentences to 2nd degree.  The medical board lawsuit did not stop executions so the tactics will continue.  It is quite clear that this bill is another step to end executions, and you must know that these murderers are evil with no regard for human life, and there is huge support from the citizens for capital punishment. 

Following is some information from the Center for Death Penalty Litigation which was compiled for a Forsyth County murderer, Thomas Michael Larry:

The Center for Death Penalty Litigation study examined all Forsyth County
murders from 1993 to 2003:
There were 383 murderers
247 murderers were black (64.4%)
83 murderers were white (21.6%)
1 murderer was Native American (0.2%)
52 murderers were of Unknown race (13.5%)
There were 25 capital trials in Forsyth County
17 whites and blacks received the death penalty
10 who received the death penalty were black (58.8%)
7 who received the death penalty were white (41.1%)
Only 1 black received the death penalty for killing a white (during a
robbery) (Note: The defendant, Robbie Lyons, first went to reform school at
age 8. During the trial, Lyons threw a rolodex at the judge.)
6 blacks received the death penalty for killing other blacks
3 blacks received the death penalty for killing Hispanics
8 whites and blacks who were tried capitally did not received the death
penalty
Of those 8 who did not received the death penalty, 5 were black, 2 were
white and 1 was Hispanic

Only one was executed for murdering a white person, my husband Stephen Stafford and that is the reason I am an advocate today for the murdered victim as their voice has been silenced.

Please do not support this unjust bill and vote "NO"

Ramona Stafford





